Spectacular jump in "wingsuit" over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez skipped a helicopter over Bogota, the capital of Colombia on Thursday.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination of wings), it went 160 km/h over the famous Monserrate sanctuary, located more than 3,000 metres above sea level, where many baths had gathered to observe its exploitation.
A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners have difficulty finding the money needed to repair the road infrastructure at a low rate, many of them come up with a solution in the form of a small black box that stands above the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile of a motorist's journey and transmit the information to public servants, are at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and government planning offices to reform the obsolete system of financing the major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of planning of major axes has suddenly led to a lively debate and energized alliances.
The libertarians joined environmental groups to put pressure on the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly of the road you travel, and then to use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is landed.
The American Civil Freedoms Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while the members of Congress are unable to reach agreement on whether to continue, several States have not waited.
They are looking for ways in the next decade to move to a system that allows drivers to pay for the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental turnaround.
This is really essential for our nation.
"It's not as if we had the choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, Director General of the Southern California Association of Governments, who expects the state to begin recording the miles travelled by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in how we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with taxes paid by Americans to the pump, is financially dry.
The Americans are no longer buying as much gasoline as before.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to increase the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The fuel tax is simply not acceptable," said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His State recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"This turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term," he said.
Wonks calls this from user fees to mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces the urban Liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set out in the state's ambitious climate change laws.
But the representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa), Chairman of the Transportation Committee of the House of Representatives, said that he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Proponents of the Reason Foundation's free market also appreciate the idea of making drivers pay at the mile.
"It's not just a tax in a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits that are provided to them.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go along the road of payment to the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would cover approximately 10,000 cars.
But the President of the Chamber killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to go to work or to town.
However, several States and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to carry out the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometre fees instead of fuel taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the east coast of the United States (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is studying how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their smallest steps and actions.
"The concerns about Big Brother and such things are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at Nevada Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the Nevada CALU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to transform these devices into full location devices."
There is no need to build a huge and bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily journeys and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now moving to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location and time.
If we can do this, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California startup called True Mileage.
Originally, the company did not intend to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to break through the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have benefited the planners of the major axes because they do not use the GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you do not record and locate their speed," said Ryan Morrison, Director General of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive ways and much less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering different choices to motorists.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have equipment at all, preferring to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing appliances to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay the parking fee, provide a "drive payment" insurance and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Automobilists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits offered by the system," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate on the mile payment is not just a huge diversification.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the Bay of San Francisco area, the officials say that Congress could simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing taxes on gasoline.
An additional single or annual tax could be taxed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and on others whose vehicles do not consume much fuel, so that each pays its fair share.
"There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four unpublished listeners
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
From The Next Day, published in January, he completed a luxury re-edition scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the screen.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone hostage.
On the day of his 66th birthday, on January 8, 2013, he said that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last album, Reality, date 2003) and too few appearances in public, the English musician proved that one could still count on him to have the pop scene cut.
A feast for his fans
Don't be surprised, David Bowie had more than one lap in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke planned to reissue this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he made a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, entitled The Next Day Extra, will take the form of three discs: the original album, new studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously released clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five specially dedicated songs for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
It introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and bags, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the words...
And above all, he gives a taste of his new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and a sparsely controlled rock electricity.
Unpublished already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal his charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on canvas.
The Informer is double-faced: a worrying intro before a light cavalcade that gradually slows down to allow room for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John's Rocket Man, even Gravity?
With this played title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on earth.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would it come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, enveloping, are eager to leave the Earth.
Bowie at least enjoys playing the chameleon with these titles: turn-to-turn informant, man on board a rocket, potential Martian...
He hides and reveals at the same time, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, especially with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
Nothing surprising, therefore, that he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the L'Invitation au Voyage campaign, of the Louis Vuitton brand, of which he embodies the new face.
It will appear in one of their advertising spots, broadcast from November 10.
The Minister of Defence, Rob Nicholson, insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and emphasized that a transition process was followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and neo-Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson assured that before they were released, the members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All injured soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them is released until they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured soldiers - who do not meet the military's "universal service" rule requiring staff to be able to perform a range of tasks - to reach the 10 year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by La Presse Canadien, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, with post-traumatic stress syndrome, was released from the army despite his request to stay for another year in order to be able to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case occurred after that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who said to a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before he was ready because he did not meet the rule of universality of the service.
Mr. Hawkins stressed that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that this was completely different from wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse Canadienne Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has been struggling to determine what latitude it can grant to wounded soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not fit for the fight.
Under the current rules, the seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployment abroad, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the required length of service for retirement benefits.
The Liberal spokesman for former combatants, Jim Karygiannis, asked Wednesday for the reintegration of Corporal Hawkins, while neo-Democrat Jack Harris called for the immediate end of "this shameful practice".
