Snowden is ready to "co-operate" with Germany on the issue of US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the US intelligence prosecutor, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the National Security Agency of the United States and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers on their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he has the right to asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter to the media in Berlin on Friday, Snowden said: "Although my efforts have clearly been positive, my government continues to treat the difference of opinion as a leak and seeks to penalize the political speech with accusations against which it is impossible to defend itself."
However, saying the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he believed that the support of the international community could convince the U.S. government to abandon the criminal charges against him.
In connection with the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with spying and stealing of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, German Minister of the Interior, said at Zeit Online: "If Mr. Snowden is ready to speak to German officials, we will make this possible."
The relationship between the United States and Germany has been severely tested following complaints that NSA had been listening to the cell phone of the German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing foreign secret services, said that if there was a chance of hearing Mr. Snowden as a witness "without putting him in danger and completely ruining relations with the United States", it would have to be taken advantage of.
Mr. Ströbele, German Green MP, published a photo of him on his Twitter account with Mr. Snowden.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele stated that, according to counsel from the former NSA consultant, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Mr. Snowden testified in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be "safe" there, said the MP.
Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been subjected to a "serious and sustained" persecution campaign that forced him to leave his country.
However, he said that he had been encouraged by the global response to "my act of political expression".
Citizens around the world and senior officials – including in the United States – felt that the revelation of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance was of public use.
The letter provides an offer of cooperation with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved”.
