Frontier Airlines plans to pay for baggage by hand
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 to passengers carrying luggage on their flights.
Frontier Airlines is planning to start paying up to $100 for a hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or a soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened canoe with them to the descent of the plane.
New baggage charges apply to bags in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free of charge.
Frontier stated that it would pay $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if passengers paid only once at the boarding door.
Frontier Spokesperson Kate O'Malley indicated that the $100 was planned to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to have this price paid," she explained.
Airlines started paying first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as many things as they could in the luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in those compartments.
These fees are a means of ensuring that passengers carry less things on board.
O'Malley said that these new expenses will not really be used to raise money.
It is about making the customers of Frontier the most faithful that it becomes increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers buying tickets at the airline site will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger making the tail at a Frontier boarding door could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the tail might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of the existence of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand luggage costs will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been fixed.
Passengers often rouse about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are important and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people in Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines pay enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
However, many of them have not affected baggage costs.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first charges for hand luggage three years ago, and the low-cost Algerian company followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant to Jay Sorensen airlines, who closely follows the surcharges.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's hand luggage costs were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former manager of Midwest Airlines, recently travelled to Spirit and wondered what he was going to find at the boarding gate when passengers would discover the unusual baggage charges imposed by the company.
"I had never seen such a fluid boarding procedure in my entire career," he said.
I was expecting to see tooth crimps and a fight burst at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers are mounted on board at the speed of the lightning."
Frontier also acts as Spirit and charges $2 for a coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier has indicated that passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened cane with them, and those who take coffee can be served free of charge.
It will always distribute water for free.
US Airways briefly tried to pay for drinks in 2008, but returned seven months later after the passengers complained and while no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to pay for baggage when passengers do not buy their ticket directly from the airline is his final effort to encourage customers to go to his site.
Airlines pay online travel vendors like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This has encouraged all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half a mile of loyalty to customers who bought their ticket via an online travel agency.
Wednesday, it reduced the miles premium by 25 per cent on one trip.
For example, a 1000-mile border trip purchased from an online travel agency would make it possible to earn 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they buy their ticket directly on the Frontier site.
Frontier has a loyal customer in his home city, Denver, but his activity is back and she loses money.
Revenues fell by 9% and its flight capacity decreased by almost 13% in the first quarter, based on the financial results released on Wednesday by its parent, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to correct Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
NSA challenges an "internal error" and not computer hackers for failure of its site
