The profit of Bombardier decreased, while deliveries and orders of aircraft declined
Bombardier Inc., Canada's aeronautical and railway manufacturer, reported a 15% fall in net profit on Thursday, under pressure from a decline in orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and from contractual issues in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not provide flight test data for his brand new CSeries aircraft or information to determine whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious schedule of commercial deployment by next September.
After the initial flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the pilot only stole three times, and the question was then whether the test phase was on track.
Results were not consistent with forecasts and the share price declined by 8% at the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doersksen, an analyst at the National Bank Financial, lowered his rating from "overperformance" to "sector performance" on Thursday due to low stock market growth potential over the next quarter or two quarters.
