How biometrics will invade our lives
Ends the passwords to tap to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho , estimates that even "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in such a transversal and transnational universe as the Internet.
The organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but worry about it.
In 2011 and France alone, the National Commission for Computer Science and Freedoms authorised 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone in the world will soon be identified, anywhere and anytime," said Justin Brookman, Consumer Privacy Officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology, Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in one, and pessimism, in the other?
Biometry will be based on new technologies that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data is the fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people working on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of the field of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand involve a voluntary and specific act of the people.
It is both a safety - we cannot capture this data to their ignorance - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted over the past 20 years on other approaches, such as face or iris recognition (colored part of the eye).
These techniques become operational thanks to increased sensor accuracy and the computing capacity of computers required for data analysis.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, Director of Access R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a face or iris in motion.
"Today we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
A unique and infalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police a suitcase costing 90.000 euros to analyse DNA samples in the place of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is the person it claims to be).
The identification has so far been about the issue of identity papers: the biometric elements (prints, photographs, iris) must be confronted with the information that the State already has on all its citizens.
This helps to ensure that one person does not try to usurp the identity of another person.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We collect the images of surveillance cameras and compare them to the photographs of celebrities that freely circulate on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, responsible for commercial development at NEC France for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a quidam that makes the tail in a store, follow its progression through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening of a computer).
More recently, the presence check was added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a friend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also apply to transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric drive: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the natural security company in partnership with banks and brands of the large distribution: when paying in stores with its bank card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger in a reader who scans the veins.
Experimentation is planned to last for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer remains in cash for thirty seconds less, it is significant," explains the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if one tries to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
However, in the absence of extensive studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to worry.
"The advances in facial recognition, the increase in surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," predicts Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
