There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, as soon as a cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of a pope – that is, a group of 120 "Cerdinary Electors".
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said that a meeting bringing together all existing cardinals would take place before the ceremony during which bishops will be exalted to the dignity of the cardinal, known as the Consistory.
" Pope Francis decided to announce his decision to convene the February Consistory in advance to facilitate the planning of other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world," said Lombardi.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that by February, the number of cardinals will probably decrease.
He said that a pope generally appointed as many cardinals as necessary for the number of cardinals to reach 120 and as many cardinals over 80 years of age as he wanted.
Next year's consistory will be important because it will be the first since Pope Francis' election in March of this year," said Valero.
For the time being, there is a kind of tendency to favour Europe and, in particular, Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he added.
40% of Roman Catholics live in South America, but a small number of cardinals represent them.
The cardinals will also be the first to be chosen since François formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world charged with examining ways to reform the church.
Previously, the Pope ruled by himself.
"Now, François has chosen these eight cardinals to help," Valero explained.
He added that it was "very possible" that François asked for advice from the cardinals.
But we have never experienced such a situation – it is totally new.
Valero indicated that the popes generally raised bishops representing large communities in the rank of cardinal, but that François was "full of surprises – so we do not know who he will name".
