A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for Conservation and Study of Animals and Environment Marines (OCEAMM), is responsible for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
It's good news, but I'm not surprised.
While in the past the species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
Moreover, it is not impossible for such advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or membership of a species of a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are being challenged due to advances in genetics.
Similarly, two species very close morphologically were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific humpback dolphins and the Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is it an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had long been known by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present at this location.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral or accidental capture epidemic occurs in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered by the number of existing individuals on Earth, i.e., the stock, and the potential for recovery from neighbouring stocks.
With regard to the species Sousa chinensis, of which the population of the new species of discovery has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogenous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brew limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It must be known that the marine environment is the least well-known medium.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, only 11 kilometres from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on life research on other planets than marine research, and it's high time it changed.
