"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could receive any treatment he could receive.
"It's not easy," adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5:00, run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father's death in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country ' s health expenditure is realized in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," explained Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot benefit from life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed more than 700 surgical operations free of charge in the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé's central hospital.
And it has created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas during weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they get caught in vans after fixing the medical equipment on the roof and crossing hard terrain to get to the villages that need the most help.
Happiness does not always follow them.
They have often had to push vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best available accommodations.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr.Bwelle – with his great smile and abundant energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people every time we visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this mobile hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive beech, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the practical team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, a town hall or a house; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the first hours of the Sunday morning.
It is an escalating rhythm, but the musicians of the villages usually help the team stay motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work," said Mr. Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returned to the city, tired but proud of the work it did.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgical acts free of charge in the last year, and it knows that their presence can make the most of the difference for those to whom they come to help.
One man explained that his free operation to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," said the man.
In addition to making this mobile hospital live and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr.Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student from Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteering in Dr.Bwelle's group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association to carry out these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, it is an opportunity to learn on the ground that they do not have at home.
"We've been able to participate in operations to help suck blood or pass the instruments on to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
It is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a medical student in the second year.
Volunteer students generally pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transport and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"It's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not near to extinction.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happily while keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," added Mr. Bwelle.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons why I do this.
