John Kerry admitted, without precedent, that American espionage "had gone too far in an inappropriate way"
John Kerry pointed out that the defensive attitude of the United States towards its surveillance programs had been weakened by admitting that on several occasions espionage "had gone too far in an inappropriate way".
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, had been directed on "automatic pilot" when a series of fire-fighting revelations by declarant Edward Snowden about NSA espionage activities emerged.
The leaks put the U.S. government in the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London by video link, Mr Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned some things in automatic pilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War and up to the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course on 11 September."
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that American espionage had exceeded the limits, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said, "In some cases, it went too far in an inappropriate way."
And the President is committed to trying to clarify and clarify to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused as part of this process.
Mr. Kerry, however, insisted that NSA was a good force and that its monitoring operations had saved many lives.
He added, "We live in a new world where people are ready to jump."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try and kill people, detonate them and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they do?
We actually prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
