"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in the mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first mandate, and chairman of the Sub-Commission on European Affairs of the American Senate, during an interview since Washington.
And I am going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to combat terrorism, despite the anger caused by NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some of the US allies, but the director of the agency said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it involved metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations reported on documents disclosed by Snowden that NSA had intercepted data and communications from the cell phone of the German Chancellor Angela Merkel and from 34 other heads of state.
The intelligence director, James Clapper, justified ally espionage by indicating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a tour of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and of both chambers.
